<br>
If charmers can reliably sustain three times the damage of non-charming damage dealers in <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>PoP</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> with ordinary risk and support costs, then charmers will be chosen as damage dealers to the exclusion of non-charming damage dealers, and in particular melees.<br>
<br>
My interests are not served by such a broken, lopsided game.  Even if <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">I</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> get <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Call of the Archmage</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> and that lets me do 300-700 DPS, the game is broken.<br>
<br>
It is far more than just mages, although as damage dealers we are especially concerned.<br>
<br>
While <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Noonie</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->'s attitude is pushing the acceptable limits, her argument is sound.  If the best damage mitigation class is also the best damage dealing class, and damage mitigation and damage dealing are the only two basic functions required for a group, then enchanters are a god class.<br>
<br>
I have seen nothing from any enchanter that begins to counter this argument.<br>
